Swap memory is a portion of disk space used by the OS when RAM is full.
In CentOS (Linux):
	RAM = fast but limited 
	Swap = slow but helps avoid crashes 
Example: 
If your system has 4 GB RAM and running many processes:
	RAM gets full → Linux moves inactive data to swap 
	This prevents system from crashing (Out Of Memory) 

Why Swap is Important 
	Prevents system crash 
	Supports memory-heavy apps 
	Helps in multitasking 
	Used for hibernation (optional) 

Practical: Swap in CentOS 
1. Check Existing Swap

free -h                      /                      swapon --show

2. Create Swap File (Example: 1GB)

dd if=/dev/zero of=/swapfile bs=1M count=1024

Alternative (faster):

fallocate -l 1G /swapfile

3. Set Correct Permissions

chmod 600 /swapfile

4. Make it Swap Format

mkswap /swapfile

5. Enable Swap

swapon /swapfile

6. Verify Swap

free -h

7. Make Swap Permanent
Edit /etc/fstab:

vi /etc/fstab
Add this line:

/swapfile swap swap defaults 0 0

Check Swappiness Value

cat /proc/sys/vm/swappiness
     Default = 60
	0 → Avoid swap 
	100 → Use swap aggressively 
Change Swappiness

sysctl vm.swappiness=20

Permanent:

echo "vm.swappiness=20" >> /etc/sysctl.conf

Suppose:
	Your Docker containers / Kubernetes pods consume high memory 
	System RAM becomes full 
Without swap → Application crash
With swap → System survives, performance slows but stable

Swap is not replacement for RAM
Too much swap usage = performance issue
In cloud (AWS/Azure), often minimal swap is recommended
